%h1 Electronics Lab Essentials
%p
  A full lab is very expensive.  
  You probably can't just buy everything indicated on this page, unless you're filthy rich.  
  What you should do is decide what kind of an electronics hacker you're going to be, and buy equipment that you'll use often.  

%p
  A good lab equipment manifest helpful to others should be
%ul
  %li Modular (broken down into easily readable parts)
  %li Use a bulletted list format for quick reading
  %li Show rounded prices
  %li Show links to gain more information, either purchasing links or info pages

%p
  Thus this page.  :)  
  Idealy this page would be converted into an online, cloud based, inventory management program that allows users to track where they buy from, 
  who has better prices/ quality, and what they have in stock (or in the mail).  




%h4 Organization (required)
%p
  If you're going to work on electronics, you need a warm workbench that you can leave projects on, lots of organizers, and some storage space.  
  
%ul
  %li.required=link_to "label Maker (seriously, required)", "http://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&field-keywords=+label+maker&rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3A+label+maker"
  %li Big tubs
  %ul{style: "list-style-type: none;"}
    %li Use these tubs to put *Everything* in.  Everything should be encapsulated in smaller stackable organizers.
  %li Project Holders
  %ul{style: "list-style-type: none;"}
    %li 
      These are anything that is big enough to hold bread board, power adapters, etc and can be sealed.  
